<h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

<ul>
    <li><h4>Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)</h4></li>
    <p>
        IaaS provides virtualized computing resources over the internet. In this model:
        Users rent virtual machines, storage, networks, and operating systems from a cloud provider.
        The provider manages the underlying hardware infrastructure and
        users have control over operating systems, storage, and deployed applications.
        Examples: Amazon EC2, Microsoft Azure VMs, Google Compute Engine
    </p>
    <li><h4>Platform as a Service (PaaS)</h4></li>
    <p>
        PaaS provides a platform allowing customers to develop, run, and manage applications without the complexity of maintaining the underlying infrastructure. In this model:

        The provider manages hardware and software on its own infrastructure.
        Users focus on application development without worrying about operating systems, software updates, storage, or infrastructure and
        offers tools and services designed for software development.
        Examples: Google App Engine, Heroku, Microsoft Azure App Services
    </p>
    <li><h4>Software as a Service (SaaS)</h4></li>
    <p>
        SaaS delivers software applications over the internet, eliminating the need for users to install and run the application on their own computers. In this model:

        Applications are managed from a central location.
        Users access applications via a web browser and
        the provider handles all updates and maintenance.
        Examples: Google Workspace, Salesforce, Dropbox
    </p>
</ul>
